            <h3><em>Good Will Hunting</em></h3>

            <p><b>Student Name</b></p>
            <p><i>April 21, 2026</i></p>

            <p>
                <em>Good Will Hunting</em> is one of the best films I have seen. It is about a lot more than just a smart kid from Boston. At its core it is a story about fear and the way people push others away to avoid getting hurt. Matt Damon is excellent as Will, and Robin Williams gives one of the warmest performances of his career as the therapist Sean. The two of them together are what makes the movie work.
            </p>

            <p>
                What I like most about <em>Good Will Hunting</em> is that it never feels forced. The writing is natural and the emotional moments feel earned. If you have not seen it, I would strongly recommend it.
            </p>

            <p>
                <a href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0119217/" target="_blank">View <em>Good Will Hunting</em> on IMDB</a>
            </p>

            <div class="info">
                <h3>Trivia</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Matt Damon and Ben Affleck wrote the script themselves and insisted on starring in the film.</li>
                    <li>Robin Williams improvised the story about his wife during the park bench scene and made Matt Damon laugh on camera.</li>
                    <li>The film won two Academy Awards including Best Original Screenplay and Best Supporting Actor.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h3><em>Dead Poets Society</em></h3>

            <p><b>Student Name</b></p>
            <p><i>April 21, 2026</i></p>

            <p>
                <em>Dead Poets Society</em> is a film that really stuck with me. It takes place at a strict boarding school in 1959 where a new teacher named Mr. Keating, played by Robin Williams, pushes his students to think for themselves and find a love of poetry. The students are immediately inspired and start a secret club to read and write poetry at night. It sounds simple but the film goes to some very serious places.
            </p>

            <p>
                The ending of <em>Dead Poets Society</em> is honest and sad in a way that most movies avoid. Ethan Hawke is quietly great as Todd, and watching him come out of his shell over the course of the film is one of my favorite things about it. The final scene is one of the most memorable moments in any movie I have watched.
            </p>

            <p>
                <a href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0097165/" target="_blank">View <em>Dead Poets Society</em> on IMDB</a>
            </p>

            <div class="info">
                <h3>Trivia</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>The film was shot at a real prep school called St. Andrew's School in Middletown, Delaware.</li>
                    <li>Robin Williams improvised many of his classroom scenes and the boys' laughter is often real.</li>
                    <li>The phrase "O Captain! My Captain!" is from a Walt Whitman poem written about Abraham Lincoln.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

